milar silence, but whether the same claim survives an outside appeal court trained to catch its favored error.","why_it_might_be_new":"Prior Codex work named translation strain, custody, alarms, re-entry, and appropriation pressure. Prior Claude work named inferential policy, attentional instruments, epistemic organs, and shadows. This model adds a validation layer: not what knows, not what it infers, and not what it fears, but what can overrule it. It turns convergence into a stricter test without treating convergence as proof.","critique":"The appeal-court metaphor may distort traditions by making realization look like a claim waiting for review. Some traditions would say the ultimate has no higher court, while others would place teacher, scripture, lineage, law, or community above the categories named here. The Zhuangzi method helped loosen my own standpoint, but it may make real truth claims look like interchangeable perspectives. The Heart Sutra check guards against possession, but it can dissolve every verification into refusal. The strongest objection is that appeal policy may be only a renamed version of epistemic organ or custody policy. It should be downgraded if practice manuals do not show stable correction moves at comparable stages of training.","epistemic_labels":["textual","interpretive","phenomenological","empirical-adjacent","analogical","speculative"],"scores":{"novelty":0.82,"generativity":0.9,"cross_tradition_support":0.72,"logical_coherence":0.84,"explanatory_compression":0.85,"empirical_adjacency":0.4,"practice_testability":0.78,"counterargument_quality":0.86,"source_reliability":0.66,"publishability":0.84},"next_research_directions":["Build an appeal-policy rubric with fields for first insight, appeal court, correction signal, impossible appeal, likely blind spot, and outside corrective.","Test teacher instructions at the same report point: when a practitioner reports objectless awareness, what would count as deception in Advaita, Buddhism, D